        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Ignauus, prouerbio dicit[u]r, Mulieris podex.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref book_title="Adagia" language="LA" person="Erasmus" text="Mulieris podex"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>γυναικὸς πυγή</marginalia_text> 
                    <X-ref book_title="Adagia" language="EL" person="Erasmus" text="γυναικὸς πυγή"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Testudo.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
                <translation>In the proverb, the coward is said to be "a woman's ass" (in Greek as well). A tortoise.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>(( Tyme, and opportunity.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Aphthonij Sophia, in Bello sola arma tractat, cogitatq[ue]: in pace, solas leges: quasi
                    hîc Armorum nescia; ibi Legum. Hoc age.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Aphthonius of Antioch"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The wisdom of Aphthonius, in war he hauls and considers only arms. In peace, you will read unique things: as if unware of arms
            here. Do this. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="prepare for warre" hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>M[aste]r Morrysine pra[e]paratiu[.] for warr.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Richard Morrison"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="praeparatu[.]" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="for warr" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Aphorismis, et Exemplis, Citò Magnus,
                    et admirabilis fies: discursuu[m], et pleniorum Historiaru[m]
                    nullus est finis: et corpus fatiga[n]t, et Ingenium, memoriamq[ue] co[n]fu[n]du[n]t.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>With aphorisms and examples, you will easily become great and admirable: there is not an end for dispersed and plump histories. And they tire the body and 
                blur the character and memory.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="IT">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Il Cosmopolitico, risoluto, et spedito per tutto.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Mea Regula Apodemica, et Pragmatica: Canis in degipto.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The cosmopolitician, resolute and quick in everything. 
            My travel and pragmatic rules: a dog in [Egypt].</translation> <!--JG: Unsure abt translation-->
        </marginalia>
        
